{{Infobox protected area | name = Hatila Valley National Park | alt_name = ''Hatila Vadisi Millî Parkı'' | iucn_category = | photo = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | photo_width = | map = Turkey | map_alt = The location of the park within Turkey | map_caption = The location of the park within Turkey | map_width = | relief = yes | label = Hatila Valley NP | label_position = bottom | mark = | marker_size = | location = [[Artvin Province]], Turkey | nearest_city = [[Artvin]], Turkey | coordinates = {{coords|41|11|09|N|41|44|02|E|region:TR|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|16900|ha|abbr=on}} | designation = | authorized = | created = | established = {{start date|1994|08|31}} | designated = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_ref = | governing_body = [[Ministry of Forest and Water Management (Turkey)|Ministry of Forest and Water Management]] | administrator = | operator = | owner = | world_heritage_site = | website = | child = | embedded = }}
[[File:Kackar.png|thumb|right|The [[Kaçkar Mountains]]]] '''Hatila Valley National Park''' ({{lang-tr|Hatila Vadisi Millî Parkı}}) is a national park in [[Artvin Province]] in northeastern Turkey. It consists of a steep-sided river valley at the eastern end of the [[Kaçkar Mountains]]. The area is close to the [[Black Sea]] and has a [[Mediterranean climate]] with warm summers, cool winters and plentiful rainfall throughout the year.<ref name=Gibbons>{{cite book|author=Gibbons, Bob|title=Wildflower Wonders: The 50 Best Wildflower Sites in the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CIGaAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT165 |year=2014|publisher=A&C Black |isbn=978-1-4729-1120-9 |pages=165–168}}</ref> The valley provides habitats for a diverse community of plants and animals.<ref name=NationalPark/>
==Park== The [[Hatila River]] is a tributary of the [[Çoruh River]] and has carved out a narrow, steep-sided, V-shaped valley with many waterfalls. The rock is mostly of volcanic origin and has an unusual [[Geomorphology|geomorphologic]] structure and geology, which has created a distinctive landscape. The park occupies an area of about {{convert|16900|hectare}}.<ref name=NationalPark>{{cite web |url=http://nationalparksofturkey.com/hatila-valley-national-park/ |title=Hatila Valley National Park |publisher=National Parks of Turkey |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> The lower parts of the valley are dry and warm but the higher parts are cool and humid with snow cover in winter. The valley is densely vegetated, especially in its middle and lower sections. Between 1994 and 1997, a botanical survey carried out identified 769 [[species]] of plant in 87 [[Family (biology)|families]] and 324 [[Genus|genera]] here.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Eminagaoglu, Ozgur |author2=Anşin, Rahim |year=2003 |title=The Flora of Hatila Valley National Park and its Close Environs (Artvin) |journal=Turkish Journal of Botany |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=1–27 |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259440360_The_Flora_of_Hatila_Valley_National_Park_and_its_Close_Environs_Artvin }}</ref>
==Flora== [[File:Primula, from Riza DSC071156565.JPG|thumb|right|Primula vulgaris'' subsp. ''sibthorpii'']] The forests on the mountain slopes in the park consist of both deciduous and evergreen tree species. These include [[Quercus petraea|sessile oak]], [[Castanea sativa|sweet chestnut]], [[Carpinus orientalis|oriental hornbeam]], [[Carpinus betulus|common hornbeam]], [[Alnus glutinosa|black alder]], [[Fagus orientalis|oriental beech]], [[Picea orientalis|oriental spruce]], [[Abies nordmanniana|Caucasian fir]] and [[Scots pine]]. On the higher slopes, the [[Populus tremula|common aspen]] is added to these as well as [[rhododendron]], [[juniper]], ''[[Vaccinium]]'', [[willow]], [[birch]] and [[Rubus idaeus|European raspberry]].<ref name=Baskaya/>
The Hatila Valley has a very rich flora and a long botanical season, with different flowering periods for different zones depending on altitude. In spring in the lower parts of the valley, forest clearings are abloom with [[hellebore]]s, magenta ''[[Cyclamen coum]]'', blue [[Omphalodes cappadocica|Cappadocian navelwort]] and pink [[Primula vulgaris|''Primula vulgaris'' subsp. ''sibthorpii'']]. Higher up the valley, and a few weeks later, ''[[Primula vulgaris]]'' flowers profusely and at least five species of [[Galanthus|snowdrop]] grow here including the recently described ''[[Galanthus koenenianus]]''.<ref name=Gibbons/> The hay meadows and forest glades at higher elevations are at their best around midsummer. Here bloom several species of [[Geranium psilostemon|cranesbill]], including the [[Geranium psilostemon|Armenian cranesbill]], [[Trollius|globe flower]], [[Pedicularis|lousewort]] and a variety of terrestrial [[Orchidaceae|orchids]]. Higher still, the forest gives way to scrubland with [[Rhamnus (genus)|buckthorn]], [[birch]] and rhododendron including the yellow-flowered ''[[Rhododendron luteum]]''. Here there grow yellow [[Lilium|lilies]], [[Paeonia wittmanniana|Wittmann's paeony]] and the blue and white-flowered ''[[Aquilegia olympica]]''. Higher still there is moorland and alpine pastures with many species of bulbous plants including [[Ornithogalum|stars of Bethlehem]], ''[[Scilla siberica]]'' and ''[[Scilla rosenii]]''. Among the short grasses grow [[primula]]s, including ''[[Primula auricula]]'' in damp spots, [[Gentiana|gentians]], [[Viola lutea|mountain pansies]], [[Campanula|bellflowers]] and [[Stachys|betony]]. In the autumn there are several varieties of [[crocus]], and also [[colchicum]].<ref name=Gibbons/>
==Fauna== [[File:Tetras du caucase jogo 0g.jpg|thumb|right|[[Caucasian grouse]]]] The natural forest of Hatila Valley National Park and the surrounding area is rich in wildlife. Large mammals found here include [[grey wolf]], [[red fox]], [[lynx]], [[leopard]], [[brown bear]], [[wild goat]], [[chamois]], [[roe deer]], [[wild boar]] and [[European hare]]. Many birds of prey pass through during their migrations, and [[golden eagle]], [[long-legged buzzard]], [[peregrine falcon]], [[Caspian snowcock]], [[Caucasian grouse]], [[chukar partridge]] and [[grey partridge]] can be seen here.<ref name=Baskaya>{{cite journal |author=Baskaya, Sagdan |year=2003 |title=Distribution and principal threats to Caucasian black grouse ''Tetrao mlokosiewiczi'' in the Eastern Karadeniz Mountains in Turkey |journal=Wildlife Biology |volume=9 |pages=377–383|url=http://www.ktu.edu.tr/dosyalar/15_04_00_5d098.pdf }}</ref>
==Facilities== The park is approached by a {{convert|10|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} road from [[Artvin]]. Accommodation is available in bungalows, caravans or tents.<ref name=kulturturizm>{{cite web |url=http://www.kultur.gov.tr/EN,36296/artvin---hatila-valley-national-park.html |title=Artvin – Hatila Valley National Park |publisher=kulturturizm.gov.tr |accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>
