==Most prominent summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Most prominent summits}}
{{main|List of the most prominent summits of Canada}}
{{see also|List of the ultra-prominent summits of Canada}}
Of the 50 most prominent summits of Canada, only Mount Logan exceeds {{convert|4000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence, five peaks exceed {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, 41 peaks exceed {{convert|2000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, and all 50 peaks equal or exceed {{convert|1866|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence.  All of these peaks are [[List of Ultras of Canada|ultra-prominent summits]].

Of these 50 peaks, 34 are located in British Columbia, nine in Yukon, six in Nunavut, and three in Alberta.  Three of these peaks lie on the international border between Yukon and Alaska, one lies on the international border between British Columbia and Alaska, two lie on the border between British Columbia and Alberta, and two lie on the border between British Columbia and Yukon.
{{clear}}
