'''Operation Safehaven''' was an [[Allies of World War II|Anglo-American]] program created in December 1944 to locate [[Nazi Germany|German]] assets in the [[Neutral powers during World War II|neutral powers]] and steer them into "safe havens", generally British or American humanitarian organizations, after [[World War II]].<ref>[[Richard Breitman]] (2008), "Review of ''Safehaven: The Allied Pursuit of Nazi Assets Abroad'' by Martin Lorenz-Meyer", ''Journal of Cold War Studies'' '''10'''(3): 164–66.</ref> The overall objective of the operation was to dissipate Nazi wealth in order to render any possible post-war resurgence (a so-called "[[Fourth Reich]]") controllable and to make it impossible for Germany to start another war.<ref>Korcaighe P. Hale (2009), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20720320?pq-origsite=summon&seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents "The Limits of Diplomatic Pressure: Operation Safehaven and the Search for German Assets in Ireland"], ''Irish Historical Studies'' '''36'''(143): 389–406.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Steury|first1=Donald P.|title=The OSS and Project SAFEHAVEN Tracking Nazi "Gold"|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/csi-studies/studies/summer00/art04.html|website=CIA.gov|publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>
